I've tried all kinds of different approaches - brute force, regexes, looking-for-missing-characters and so on, but couldn't find a reliable solution for a reasonably general-purpose input.

Answering all the questions that aren't multiple choice requires more or less the same approach: scan the input until you find a space or newline. Store the input in a string and then split on the delimiter between words - I used "and".

Most questions require you to sum up some part of the input, so you can use something like

\begin{code}
int total = 0;
for(int i = 0; i < input.length(); i++) {
    int sum = 0;
    for(int j = i; j < input.length(); j++) {
        if(isAlphanumeric(input.charAt(j))) {
            if(j + 1 == input.length()) break;
            char ch = input.charAt(j);
            if(ch =='') continue;
            total += sum + input.charAt(++j) - '0';
        }
        if(ch == 'x') if(isNumeric(input.charAT(j))) {
             total += ch - '0' + input.charAt
        }
    }
}
\end{code}

